\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 //Diagram comparing Consolas to Calibri, IBM Plex Sans Mono to IBM Plex Sans, Ubuntu to Ubuntu Mono, Fira Mono to Fira Sans, Roboto Mono to Roboto, Amazon Ember to Amazon Ember Mono.}
\par\plain \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 JetBrains Mono is my current choice of monospaced font as it has clear lettering and is readable. When choosing a monospaced font for e-book development I would recommend checking the quote marks as they are often not clear at smaller sizes. //example}
\par\plain \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\qc\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 A comparison of Roboto Mono and JetBrains Mono.}
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ltrch\loch \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f1\fs28\b1\i0 Character encoding standards:}
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 To make writing systems work on computers there are two main standards for character encoding, the American Standard Code for Information Interchange (ASCII) and it\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s successor Unicode.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 ASCII was simplistic and only defined the uppercase and lowercase English alphabet, numbers, a select group of symbols and a set of invisible control characters.}
\par\plain \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\qc\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 \{$SCRImageLink[w:500;h:286]=C:/Users/hmotley/GitHub/ebookbuild/docs/assets/Printable_ASCII_characters.png\}}
\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0 These are all of the printable ASCII characters}
\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0 //I\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92ll redo this diagram}
\par\plain \f2\fs22\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 Unicode is instead a more complete representation of the world\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s writing systems and supports over 150 different languages both modern and ancient.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 Each supported glyph within Unicode is part of a group of glyphs called a block. As it\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s a superset of ASCII, the first block called Basic Latin contains all the ASCII characters. If you need a particular character it is likely already available in a Unicode block, though keep in mind very few fonts support Unicode completely.}
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 It\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s also worth knowing about Windows Glyph List (WGL) fonts}
\par\plain \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 Ligatures}
\par\plain \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\plain {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 Ligatures are two or more conjoined glyphs that usually (though not always) provide improved readability and are used for aesthetic purposes. As with any typographical feature, it\loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8217\'92s support may vary between each e-reader and should not be guaranteed.}
\par\plain \f2\fs28\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\qc\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 \{$SCRImageLink[w:160;h:112]=C:/Users/hmotley/GitHub/ebookbuild/docs/assets/ligature_example.png\}}
\par\plain {\f2\fs22\b0\i0 The letters \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93fi\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93fl\u8221\'94 are commonly presented as a ligature}
\par\plain \f2\fs22\b0\i0
\par\pard\plain \tx0\tx360\tx720\tx1080\tx1440\tx1800\tx2160\tx2880\tx3600\tx4320\fi360\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs28\b0\i0 Some characters such as the ampersand (&) were previously ligatures that became a individual glyph over time.}
